,Recommended,416060,34246655,Posted: 14 August,all,Deacon Syre,"It's good but I found myself fighting the controls and the camera a lot. You need to click (repeatedly) on an enemy to shoot them but the mouse pointer is so small and basically the same color as the world so I kept losing it when things got hot. Even at 1920x1080 I was having trouble spotting the items in the world you could pick up (which you need to do to survive and complete quests).I felt the stamina system was a waste and just meant I had to waste time waiting for a bar to refill while I'm trying to explore a map. I guess it's meant to stop you from kiting or something. I dunno.The stealth mechanic works excellent, so I spent most of my time walking to take full advantage of it, only running when I needed to escape or cover uncontested ground.I've only tried pistols and assault rifles so far and enjoyed them both. I think the rocket barrage skill or whatever that the cyborg starts with is messed up. The rockets travel at like walking speed. So, by the time you realize you're jammed up, launched them, and they've travel whatever distance you put between you and the enemies (which should be healthy to avoid rocket damage) I've lost more health than if I had just popped any other skill and mowed them down.I haven't played enough to tell if putting points into skill cooldown reduction makes a good dent because the skill cooldowns are loooong.All in all, I'm glad I got it and I might come back."
76561198083871385,Recommended,416060,34480914,Posted: 25 August,all,Seandginley,"I don't typically review my titles, but I noticed in the comments section this game is getting a lot of criticism that I feel is misleading. In the negative reviews, it keeps coming back to two features:1) The movement system is bad2) The game (or some aspect of it) is too hardSo here's the thing, the movement system isn't BAD, it's just different... very different to a point where it feels weird when you first start playing. That is not inherently a flaw though... I'd say I found League of Legends use of right clicking more unintuitive, and certainly harder to adjust to. Really, it's pretty simple, you just need to het the hang of it... Mouse scroll up to run and down to walk, click to move-to, holded shift to stop or alt to crouch to switch your mouse clicks to aim and fire rather than move-to. That's really all there is to it, for all reviewers keep ranting about how awful it is. I think I basically adjusted after 20 minutes. No, there is no cover mechanic, the idea is you walk to approach in stealth if that's your plan, or just run around a corner and get firing if not. You can abandon a fight and run back around a corner (or down a hall!) if you want to stick and move (it is useful for healing, admittedly, but usually the idea is whether because you dash in suddenly guns blazing or tiptoe in unheard, your statedy is close distance and mow the bad guys down.As for difficulty, the game actually isn't hard per say, rather it just doesn't hold your hand. The tutorial is brusqe (because who likes long tutorials?) and from there, the game expects you to really use the info it gave you, pay attention to your UI, and figure out the details of what information you have and what you're able to do via observation and expeirmentation. The closest I'll come to saying it's ""hard"" is that these are skills an experienced gamer is much more likely to have... but it's like knowing enough to look at the deeper menus of a game like Final Fantasy Tactics or Disgaea with the comprehension that if the devs put it there, there's information worth knowing. If you use all the info and tools the game gives you, it's really not hard at all.A good example is ""There's so many enemies, not enough ammo"". Initially I had this same problem, but realized it's because I was missing most of the item drops because they're very hard to see in the game... that said, you don't NEED to see them, your map displays all of their localation of every item in the zone you haven't gotten yet... just follow it around to collect them all, and you should have plenty of ammo... but you can sneak past foes or do melee takedowns on lone targes it will help too.All in all, the game is differnet, interesting, and pretty fun, you just need to learn to play. Consider it despite the nay-sayers if it sounds fun, at least for  a sale price"
76561198013328690,Recommended,416060,34300984,Posted: 16 August,all,rasabt,"This is sorta a iso-shooter-arpg, with many mechanics reminding one of games like old-school-Diablo (skill-progression, loot, controls) just with guns. But there is a lot more to it: the game realy captures this cyberpunk/distopian-flair and the guns sound and feel great (from miniguns, to snipers and assault riffels, etc. ). The knockback-value most of your and your enemy attacks have makes it feel less spammy more like a tactical shooter; simply running into a pack of 3-4 swat-members will only get your character riddled with bullets and thus staggered ...but the very same goes for enemies aswell. Once you get used to the shooting the game is great fun.All 3 chars share the same skill-tree, but start with different starter skills; skills range from more (specific) gun-damage special effects to more damage when kneeing and less stagger, a shield , homing rockets...there's decent stuff here and some possibilities to play around with.The game mostly consists of straight foreward (small) missions, very rarely you will find npcs with sidequest or traders. The story is nothing to write home about, but it works and there's also quite good voicework here.What makes this game very unique is the quality of animations, the art-style and the amazing soundtrack, aswell as the gun-play.Don't expect some big-publisher-esque-level of content or polish, but the game is very enjoyable for what it is."
